UID:86377-1772996400-1773001800@bangaloreinternationalcentre.org
SUMMARY:What She Said
DESCRIPTION:Language: English \nWhat She Said explores the lives of six epic women spanning three mythic kingdoms. In order of appearance\, they are Sita’s sister Urmila\, Kaikeyi’s confidante Manthara\, Ravana’s sister Surpanakha\, Vali’s consort Tara\, Ravana’s queen Mandodari\, and the forgotten Shanta\, Rama’s sister. \nWhile the original epic might relegate these women to supporting characters\, Gowri Ramnarayan fashions them as individuals in their own right. In her blazingly original script\, their voices emerge as complex\, intelligent\, and authentic in bearing witness to injustice and atrocity\, as worthy of attention as that of Sita. Two characters are instrumental in driving the action. Manthara’s blind love turns Queen Kaikeyi into an outcast reviled by everyone around her. Disfigured by the prince whose love she desired\, forest dweller Surpanakha discovers the price of vengeance. \nTheir husbands’ lust towards the wives of other men turn two wise queens into tragic victims. When mighty monkey king Vali is killed\, his consort Tara has to live on\, despite being relegated to a serving woman\, in order to protect her son Angadha. Mandodari of Lanka is forced to watch her Ravana rush into the flames\, dragging his whole clan with him. \nThen there are the nonentities. Sita’s sister Urmila remains one step behind\, with a husband (Lakshmana) who has no qualms about abandoning her as he follows his brother into exile. Few know Rama’s sister Shanta even by name. Her birth father Dasaratha gives her away to his friend King Romapada\, and Romapada gives her away to a man who saves his kingdom. \nAs the play unfolds in six episodes\, each woman’s monologue provides perspectives simultaneously unique and universal. Ancient myth morphs into contemporary reality\, raising ethical questions that still haunt us in times of war\, inequality\, social-political fracture\, and ecological crisis. \nThis event is a part of our programming to celebrate International Women’s Day. Music\, theatre\, and conversation: by women\, for everyone. \nSupported by:\n \n
URL:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/event/what-she-said/
LOCATION:Bangalore International Centre\, 7\, 4th Main Road\, Domlur II Stage\, Bangalore\, Karnataka\, 560071\, India
CATEGORIES:Gender,Mythology,Performing Arts,Theatre
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/wp-content/uploads/Thumbnail_WSS.jpg
END:VEVENT
